018 Monaco Grand Prix|publisher=FORMULA 1|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nLeclerc has an older brother, Lorenzo, and a younger brother, Arthur. His father, Herv\u00e9, also raced cars, driving in Formula 3 in the 1980s and 1990s, and was well respected in karting. He died after a long illness, aged 54, just four days before his son won the feature race at the [[2017 Baku FIA Formula 2 round|2017 Formula 2 Baku weekend]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cikfia.com/newsroom/view/article/herve-leclerc-passes-away.html|title=Herv\u00e9 Leclerc passes away : CIKFIA|last=CIKFIA|website=www.cikfia.com|language=en-EN|access-date=8 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/130319|title=Charles Leclerc: Emotional Baku Formula 2 pole was for late father|last=Kalinauckas|first=Valentin Khorounzhiy and Alex|work=Autosport.com|access-date=8 August 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe was in a relationship with the Italian, Monaco-based university student Giada Gianni from January 2015 until September 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://celebritywshow.com/sport/who-is-charles-leclercs-girlfriend-giada-gianni-when-did-the-ferrari-f1-ace-start-dating-her-and-is-he-related-to-jules-bianchi/|title=Who is Charles Leclerc's girlfriend Giada Gianni, when did the Ferrari F1 ace start dating her and is he related to Jules Bianchi?|date=2019-03-17|website=CelebrityWShow|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|March 2020}}, he is in a relationship with Monaco-based model, Instagram influencer and architecture student Charlotte Sin\u00e9.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.essentiallysports.com/f1-ferrari-who-is-charles-leclerc-new-girlfriend-charlotte-sine/ |title=Who is Charles Leclerc\u2019s New Girlfriend Charlotte Sin\u00e9? |website=www.essentiallysports.com |first=Dhruv|last=George |date=25 March 2020 |access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBesides his native French, Leclerc also speaks Italian and English.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aXQFYsDFn1w|title=Intervista a Charles Leclerc|publisher=Motorsport.it Youtube Channel|date=17 February 2018|accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=N}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{official website|http://www.charles-leclerc.com/}}\n*{{DriverDB driver|charles-leclerc}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports}}\n{{Succession box | before = [[Antonio Fuoco]] | title = [[Formula Renault 2.0 Alps]]<br>Junior Champion | years = [[2014 Formula Renault 2.0 Alps Series|2014]] | after = [[Matevos Isaakyan]]}}\n{{Succession box| before = [[Esteban Ocon]] | title = [[FIA Formula 3 European Championship]]<br>Rookie Champion | years = [[2015 FIA Formula 3 European Championship|2015]] | after = [[Joel Eriksson (racing driver)|Joel Eriksson]]}}\n{{Succession box| before = [[Esteban Ocon]] | title = [[GP3 Series]]<br>Champion | years = [[2016 GP3 Series|2016]] | after = [[George Russell (racing driver)|George Russell]]}}\n{{Succession box| before = [[Pierre Gasly]]<br>(GP2 Series)| title = [[FIA Formula 2 Championship]]<br>Champion | years = [[2017 FIA Formula 2 Championship|2017]] | after = [[George Russell (racing driver)|George Russell]]}}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{Succession box| before = [[Kevin Hansen (racing driver)|Kevin Hansen]] | title = [[FIA Prize Giving Ceremony#Rookie of the Year|FIA Rookie of the Year]] | years = 2017\u20132018 | after = Incumbent}}\n{{Succession box| before = [[Pascal Wehrlein]] | title = [[Autosport Awards]]<br />Rookie of the Year | years = 2017\u20132018 | after = [[Alexander Albon]] }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Formula One teams}}\n{{Sauber}}\n{{Scuderia Ferrari}}\n{{Autosport Rookie of the Year}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leclerc, Charles}}\n[[Category:1997 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Formula Renault Eurocup drivers]]\n[[Category:FIA Formula 2 Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:FIA Formula 3 European Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:Formula Renault 2.0 Alps drivers]]\n[[Category:GP3 Series Champions]]\n[[Category:GP3 Series drivers]]\n[[Category:Karting World Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:Monegasque racing drivers]]\n[[Category:People from Monte Carlo]]\n[[Category:Monegasque Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:Sauber Formula One drivers]]\n[[Category:Ferrari Formula One drivers]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{short description|Monegasque racing driver}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox F1 driver\n| name              = Charles Leclerc\n| image             = F12019 Schloss Gabelhofen (25).jpg\n| imagesize         = \n| caption           = Leclerc in 2019\n| nationality       = {{flagicon|MCO}} Mon\u00e9gasque\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1997|10|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Monte Carlo]], Monaco \n \n\n<!-- Please leave the 2020 team in the infobox until at least 1 January 2021, per WP:F1 convention -->\n| 2020 Team         = [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.speedcafe.com/2018/09/15/leclerc-a-long-term-commitment-for-ferrari/|title=Leclerc a long term commitment for Ferrari|first=Mat|last=Coch|date=15 September 2018|work=[[Speedcafe|speedcafe.com]]|publisher=[[Speedcafe]]|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref>\n| Car number        = 16\n| Races             = {{F1stat|LEC|entries}} ({{F1stat|LEC|starts}} starts)\n| Championships     = 0\n| Wins              = {{F1stat|LEC|wins}}\n| Podiums           = {{F1stat|LEC|podiums}}\n| Points            = {{F1stat|LEC|careerpoints}}\n| Poles             = {{F1stat|LEC|poles}}\n| Fastest laps      = {{F1stat|LEC|fastestlaps}}\n| First race        = [[2018 Australian Grand Prix]]\n| First win         = [[2019 Belgian Grand Prix]]\n| Last win          = [[2019 Italian Grand Prix]]\n| Last race         = {{Latest F1GP}}\n| Last season       = 2019\n| Last position     = 4th (264 pts)\n| website           = {{Official website|https://www.charlesleclerc.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Charles Leclerc''' ({{IPA-fr|\u0283a\u0281l l\u0259kl\u025b\u0281}}; born 16 October 1997) is a [[Monaco|Mon\u00e9gasque]] racing driver, currently driving in [[Formula One]] for [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]. Leclerc won the [[GP3 Series]] championship in [[2016 GP3 Series|2016]] and the [[FIA Formula 2 Championship]] in [[2017 FIA Formula 2 Championship|2017]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Allen|first1=Peter|title=Leclerc is GP3 champion despite collision as De Vries wins|url=http://www.formulascout.com/leclerc-is-gp3-champion-despite-collision-as-de-vries-wins/35825|accessdate=14 May 2017|work=formulascout.com|date=26 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.autosport.com/f2/news/132272/leclerc-seals-f2-title-with-jerez-win|title=Leclerc seals F2 title with Jerez win|work=[[Autosport]].com|publisher=[[Motorsport Network]]|date=7 October 2017|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nLeclerc made his Formula One debut in {{f1|2018}} for [[Sauber Motorsport|Sauber]], a team affiliated with Ferrari, for which he was part of [[Ferrari Driver Academy]]. With Sauber having finished last the year before, Leclerc led the charge to improve the finishing position in the constructors' championship to eighth, being the higher ranked of the two Sauber drivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sauberf1team.com/news/2018-formula-one-etihad-airways-abu-dhabi-grand-prix-race-sunday|title=2018 Formula One Etihad Airways Abu Dhabi Grand Prix - Race - Sunday|publisher=Alfa Romeo Sauber F1|date=25 November 2018|accessdate=1 December 2018}}</ref> Starting from {{f1|2019}} and until the end of the 2024 season,<ref name=Leclerc2024>{{cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/leclerc-ferrari-contract-2024-vettel/4616117/|title=Leclerc extends Ferrari F1 contract until 2024|last=Elizalde|first=Pablo|date=23 December 2019|accessdate=23 December 2019|publisher=Motorsport.com}}</ref> Leclerc will be driving for Ferrari. He became the second-youngest driver to qualify on pole position in Formula One during his first Ferrari season in [[2019 Bahrain Grand Prix|Bahrain]]. The 2019 season also saw Leclerc take his first career win in [[2019 Belgian Grand Prix|Belgium]], followed by winning his first [[2019 Italian Grand Prix|Italian Grand Prix]] as a Ferrari driver the week after. He won the [[FIA Pole Trophy|Pole Trophy]] in the 2019 F1 season becoming the youngest driver ever and the first non-[[Mercedes-Benz in Formula One|Mercedes]] driver to win it.\n\n==Early career==\n===2005\u20132013: Karting===\nLeclerc began his [[karting]] career in 2005, winning the French [[Provence-Alpes-C\u00f4te d'Azur|PACA]] Championship in 2005, 2006 and 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.allroadmanagement.com/charles-leclerc.htm|title=Charles Leclerc|publisher=All Road Management|work=allroadmanagement.com|accessdate=2 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706223024/http://www.allroadmanagement.com/charles-leclerc.htm|archive-date=6 July 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2009 he became French Cadet champion before moving up to the [[KF3]] class in 2010, where he won the [[Junior Monaco Kart Cup]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Monaco Kart Cup&nbsp;\u2013 KF3 2010 standings|work=driverdb.com|publisher=Driver Database|url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/monaco-kart-cup---kf3/2010/|accessdate=2 January 2015}}</ref> He continued in the KF3 class for 2011, winning the [[Commission Internationale de Karting|CIK]]-[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile|FIA]] KF3 World Cup, the CIK-FIA Karting Academy Trophy and the ERDF Junior Kart Masters.<ref>{{cite news|title=Karting details&nbsp;\u2013 the karting career of Charles Leclerc|work=driverdb.com|publisher=Driver Database|url=https://www.driverdb.com/drivers/charles-leclerc/|accessdate=2 January 2015}}</ref> During the year, Leclerc also became a member of [[Nicolas Todt]]'s All Road Management company.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.allroadmanagement.com/about.htm|title=All Road Management&nbsp;\u2013 About Us|publisher=All Road Management|work=allroadmanagement.com|accessdate=2 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161222110618/http://www.allroadmanagement.com/about.htm|archive-date=22 December 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nLeclerc graduated to the [[KF2]] category in 2012 with the [[factory-backed]] [[ART Grand Prix]] team, winning the WSK Euro Series title,<ref>{{cite news|title=ART Grand Prix and Charles Leclerc conquered the WSK Euro Series championship in Zuera|work=karting.art-grandprix.com|publisher=[[ART Grand Prix]]|url=http://karting.art-grandprix.com/news/art-grand-prix-and-charles-leclerc-conquered-wsk-euro-series-championship-zuera|date=6 August 2012|accessdate=2 January 2015}}</ref> as well as finishing runner-up in the CIK-FIA European KF2 Championship and the CIK-FIA Under 18 World Karting Championship.<ref>{{cite news|title=Charles Leclerc|work=karting.art-grandprix.com|publisher=[[ART Grand Prix]]|url=http://karting.art-grandprix.com/racing/kz/drivers/charles-leclerc|accessdate=2 January 2015}}</ref> In his final year of karting in 2013, Leclerc won the South Garda Winter Cup and claimed sixth position in the CIK-FIA European [[KZ1 (karting)|KZ]] Championship and finished second in the CIK-FIA World KZ Championship, behind current [[Red Bull Racing|Red Bull]] [[Formula One]] driver [[Max Verstappen]].<ref>{{cite news|title=CIK-FIA World KZ Championship 2013 standings|work=driverdb.com|publisher=Driver Database|url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/world-championship-kz/2013/|accessdate=2 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u20132016: Formula Renault, Formula Three and GP3===\nIn 2014 following a crash at the Japanese Grand Prix, Charles lost his lifelong friend and godfather [[Jules Bianchi]]. In 2014, Leclerc graduated to [[open wheel car|single-seaters]], racing in the [[2014 Formula Renault 2.0 Alps Series|Formula Renault 2.0 Alps]] championship for [[Great Britain|British]] team [[Fortec Motorsport]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.paddockscout.com/leclerc-teams-up-with-fortec-for-alps-campaign/|title=Leclerc teams up with Fortec for Alps campaign|last=Goddard|first=Stephen|date=26 November 2013|publisher=Paddock Scout|work=paddockscout.com|accessdate=2 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107103954/http://www.paddockscout.com/leclerc-teams-up-with-fortec-for-alps-campaign|archive-date=7 November 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> During the season, he took seven podium positions, including a double victory at [[Autodromo Nazionale Monza|Monza]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.paddockscout.com/charles-leclerc-grabs-second-win-of-monza-weekend/|title=Charles Leclerc grabs second win of Monza weekend|last=Khorounzhiy|first=Valentin|date=6 July 2014|publisher=Paddock Scout|work=paddockscout.com|accessdate=2 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171203013817/http://www.paddockscout.com/charles-leclerc-grabs-second-win-of-monza-weekend|archive-date=3 December 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> to finish runner-up in the championship behind [[Koiranen GP]]'s [[Nyck de Vries]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Formula Renault 2.0 Alps 2014 standings|work=driverdb.com|publisher=Driver Database|url=https://www.driverdb.com/championships/standings/formula-renault-20-alps/2014/|accessdate=2 January 2015}}</ref> Leclerc also won the Junior Championship title at the final race of the season in [[Circuito de Jerez|Jerez]], finishing ahead of [[Russia]]n teenager [[Matevos Isaakyan]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://fortecmotorsports.com/?p=2276|title=Leclerc takes Rookie Championship title|date=8 October 2014|publisher=[[Fortec Motorsport]]s|work=fortecmotorsports.com|accessdate=2 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nLeclerc also took part in a partial [[2014 Eurocup Formula Renault 2.0|Eurocup Formula Renault 2.0]] season with Fortec as a guest driver. In the six races he contested he finished on the podium three times, taking a second place at the [[N\u00fcrburgring]] followed by a pair of second-place finishes at the [[Hungaroring]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.paddockscout.com/paddockscout-top-50-drivers-of-2014-20-11/|title=PaddockScout Top 50 drivers of 2014: 20\u201311|last=Allen|first=Peter|date=18 December 2014|publisher=Paddock Scout|work=paddockscout.com|accessdate=2 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171009093236/http://www.paddockscout.com/paddockscout-top-50-drivers-of-2014-20-11|archive-date=9 October 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nLeclerc graduated to [[Formula Three]] in 2015, racing in the [[2015 FIA Formula 3 European Championship|FIA Formula 3 European Championship]] with [[Netherlands|Dutch]] team [[Van Amersfoort Racing]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Nicolas Todt protege Charles Leclerc secures F3 deal for 2015|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/117356|first=Marcus|last=Simmons|work=[[Autosport]]|publisher=[[Haymarket Media Group|Haymarket Publications]]|date=14 January 2015|accessdate=14 January 2015}}</ref> At the opening round of the season in [[Silverstone Circuit|Silverstone]], Leclerc inherited [[pole position]] for the second and third races of the weekend after original pole-sitter [[Felix Rosenqvist]] was excluded for a technical infringement.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rosenqvist excluded from second qualifying, Leclerc inherits two poles|url=http://www.paddockscout.com/rosenqvist-excluded-from-second-qualifying-leclerc-inheirts-two-poles/26272|first=Peter|last=Allen|work=paddockscout.com|publisher=Paddock Scout|date=11 April 2015|accessdate=12 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170603081653/http://www.paddockscout.com/rosenqvist-excluded-from-second-qualifying-leclerc-inheirts-two-poles/26272|archive-date=3 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> He went on to take his first race victory in the third race of the weekend, ahead of [[Antonio Giovinazzi]] and [[Jake Dennis]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Charles Leclerc gets victory in final race of debut F3 weekend|url=http://www.paddockscout.com/charles-leclerc-gets-victory-in-final-race-of-debut-f3-weekend/26376|first=Peter|last=Allen|work=paddockscout.com|publisher=Paddock Scout|date=12 April 2015|accessdate=12 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170602235111/http://www.paddockscout.com/charles-leclerc-gets-victory-in-final-race-of-debut-f3-weekend/26376|archive-date=2 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> He took his second victory at the following round in [[Hockenheimring|Hockenheim]], winning the third race as well as taking two additional podiums and three rookie victories over the course of the event.<ref>{{cite news|title=Charles Leclerc wins wet third European F3 race at Hockenheim|url=http://www.paddockscout.com/charles-leclerc-wins-wet-third-european-f3-race-at-hockenheim/27335|first=Peter|last=Allen|work=paddockscout.com|publisher=Paddock Scout|date=3 May 2015|accessdate=3 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906074953/http://www.paddockscout.com/charles-leclerc-wins-wet-third-european-f3-race-at-hockenheim/27335|archive-date=6 September 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Leclerc scored his third win in the first race at [[Circuit de Spa-Francorchamps|Spa-Francorchamps]] which saw him take the lead in the championship. However, Leclerc finished fourth in the standings, mostly due to damage sustained to his car's chassis following a collision with [[Lance Stroll]] at [[Circuit Park Zandvoort|Zandvoort]].\n\nIn November 2015, Leclerc finished second at the [[2015 Macau Grand Prix|Macau Grand Prix]].\n\nIn December 2015, Leclerc partook in post-season testing with [[ART Grand Prix]] and [[Arden International]]. In February 2016, de Vries confirmed that Leclerc would race in the [[2016 GP3 Series|2016 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motorsport.com/gp3/news/de-vries-joins-2016-gp3-field-with-art-675332/|title=De Vries joins 2016 GP3 field with ART|date=24 February 2016|accessdate=24 February 2016|quote=\"We have Charles Leclerc, Alexander Albon [neither confirmed yet], Jake Hughes, Jack Aitken and Kevin Jorg lining up on the grid and Antonio Fuoco is staying for another season. All these guys are capable of winning races\"}}</ref> ART signed Leclerc the following week. With the team, he claimed three victories and took the title in Abu Dhabi, despite crashing out in the feature race.\n\n===2017: FIA Formula 2 Championship===\n[[File:Charles Leclerc Jerez 2017.jpg|alt=Charles Leclerc crossing the start/finish line at Jerez in 2017|thumb|Leclerc leading the Jerez feature race, on his way to winning the Formula 2 championship]]\n\nThe week following his victory in the GP3 title race, Charles Leclerc was confirmed to be graduating to the Formula 2 series for the [[2017 FIA Formula 2 Championship|2017 season]] with [[Prema Powerteam|Prema Racing]], alongside fellow GP3 racer and Ferrari junior [[Antonio Fuoco]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.racer.com/international-racing/item/136792-ferrari-juniors-to-prema-in-gp2-for-2017|title=GP2: Ferrari juniors to Prema for 2017|date=28 November 2016|accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe made his debut at [[2017 Bahrain FIA Formula 2 round|Bahrain]], where he took pole position for the feature race, but only finished third.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/128986|title=Bahrain Formula 2: Markelov beats Nato and Leclerc with late surge|last=Kalinauckas|first=Alex|work=Autosport.com|access-date=8 August 2017|language=en}}</ref> In the sprint race, his Prema team chose to take a mid-race pit stop, which is very uncommon in the shorter sprint races. He pushed harder on his medium [[Pirelli]] tyres, creating a nine-second lead before pitting. This would drop him down to 14th place, but Leclerc overtook 13 cars and took victory by overtaking [[Luca Ghiotto]] on the final lap.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/129011|title=Bahrain Formula 2: Ferrari junior Leclerc beats Ghiotto and Rowland|last=Kalinauckas|first=Alex|work=Autosport.com|access-date=8 August 2017|language=en}}</ref> After taking pole position for the second time in a row, he then fought off Ghiotto to win again in the [[2017 Catalunya FIA Formula 2 round|Catalunya]] feature race, despite a radio issue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiaformula2.com/News-Room/News/2017/05_May/Leclerc-scorches-to-feature-victory-/|title=Leclerc scorches to feature victory \u2013 Formula 2|website=www.fiaformula2.com|access-date=8 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiaformula2.com/News-Room/News/2017/05_May/Feature-Race-Press-Conference-Barcelona/|title=Feature Race Press Conference, Barcelona \u2013 Formula 2|website=www.fiaformula2.com|access-date=8 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nLeclerc did not score any points at his home round at [[Circuit de Monaco|Monaco]]. He was on pole, but retired from the lead of the race with a suspension problem. The retirement also meant he would start the sprint race from the back of the grid, and in this race he collided with [[Norman Nato]] whilst trying to make his way up the grid, which ultimately resulted in both drivers retiring from the race. He retained the championship lead despite the bad weekend, which he described as 'hugely disappointing'.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/129774|title=Monaco F2: Rowland takes first win as Leclerc retires|last=Kalinauckas|first=Alex|work=Autosport.com|access-date=8 August 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motorsport.com/fia-f2/news/monaco-f2-de-vries-rapax-sprint-race-911283/?s=1|title=Monaco F2: De Vries takes maiden win in Rapax 1\u20132|work=Motorsport.com|access-date=8 August 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.motorsport.com/fia-f2/news/charles-leclerc-column-monaco-f2-heartbreak-912533/|title=Leclerc column: Moving on from Monaco misfortune|work=Motorsport.com|access-date=8 August 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nLeclerc took a fourth consecutive pole at a race [[Baku City Circuit|Azerbaijan]], which he dedicated to his late father, Herve.<ref name=\":0\" /> He converted this into another win, although the race was red flagged five laps before the scheduled end.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/130343|title=Baku F2: Ferrari junior Charles Leclerc wins red-flagged race|last=Kalinauckas|first=Alex|work=Autosport.com|access-date=8 August 2017|language=en}}</ref> In the sprint race, he started from eighth, and dropped to tenth early on, but fought back to sixth. The retirement of the race leader, his title rival [[Oliver Rowland]], and De Vries, who was also ahead of Leclerc, meant Leclerc improved to fourth. He then passed [[Nicholas Latifi]] and [[Jordan King]], and began to close on the new leader, Nato. He passed Nato, but had been given a 10-second penalty for failing to slow for yellow flags, and therefore finished second.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiaformula2.com/Global/F2/2017/07_TheInsider/Insider2017-FIAF2-Issue4.pdf|title=Formula 2 \u2013 The Insider \u2013 Issue 4: So Close!|last=|first=|date=|website=fiaformula2.com|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Red Bull Ring|Austria]] he took his fifth pole position, and then won the feature race from pole despite coming under pressure from teammate Fuoco, and towards the end, the [[DAMS]] of Latifi.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiaformula2.com/News-Room/News/2017/07_July/Leclerc-Makes-it-Five-in-Austria/|title=Leclerc Makes it Five in Austria \u2013 Formula 2|website=www.fiaformula2.com|access-date=8 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiaformula2.com/News-Room/News/2017/07_July/Leclerc-soars-to-feature-victory/|title=Leclerc soars to feature victory \u2013 Formula 2|website=www.fiaformula2.com|access-date=8 August 2017}}</ref> He would retire from the sprint race after colliding with Fuoco and spinning out.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.autosport.com/news/report.php/id/130631|title=Artem Markelov wins Austria F2 sprint race, Charles Leclerc crashes|last=Kalinauckas|first=Alex|work=Autosport.com|access-date=8 August 2017|language=en}}</ref> By taking pole for the sixth time for the next race, at [[Silverstone Circuit|Silverstone]], he matched the record for most pole positions in a row, which was set by [[Stoffel Vandoorne]] in [[2014 GP2 Series|2014]] and [[2015 GP2 Series|2015]], when the series were called [[GP2 Series]]. He won the feature race, even after his car set alight during the race, and even after one of his wing mirrors detached in the closing stages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiaformula2.com/News-Room/News/2017/07_July/Leclerc-flies-to-five-in-Silverstone-feature/|title=Leclerc flies to five in Silverstone feature \u2013 Formula 2|website=www.fiaformula2.com|access-date=8 August 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe would not start from pole in [[Hungaroring|Hungary]], despite taking his seventh successive pole position, as he was disqualified for a technical infringement. Despite starting from the back, he was in 12th position by turn 1. Using an alternative tyre strategy that saw him start on the medium tyres, Leclerc was stuck behind [[Alexander Albon]], who was on the same strategy, although he eventually got past and would finish fourth. He would also finish fourth in the sprint race the next day, giving him a 50-point championship lead over Rowland.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiaformula2.com/News-Room/News/2017/07_July/Rowland-on-top-in-dramatic-Budapest-feature/|title=Rowland on top in dramatic Budapest feature \u2013 Formula 2|website=www.fiaformula2.com|access-date=8 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiaformula2.com/News-Room/News/2017/07_July/Matsushita-dominates-Budapest-sprint/|title=Matsushita dominates Budapest sprint \u2013 Formula 2|website=www.fiaformula2.com|access-date=8 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theinsider.fiaformula2.com/f2/issue-7-f2/stats-to-chat-7/|title=STATS TO CHAT \u2013 The Insider|website=theinsider.fiaformula2.com|language=en-GB|access-date=8 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808155414/http://theinsider.fiaformula2.com/f2/issue-7-f2/stats-to-chat-7/|archive-date=8 August 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nFor the Belgian rounds, Leclerc again took pole and won the race by a convincing margin of over 20 seconds, however his win was disqualified as one of his skidblocks was excessively worn. Having to start in 19th place, Leclerc managed to go back up to 5th place and finish 3.8 seconds behind the race winner, [[S\u00e9rgio Sette C\u00e2mara]].\n\n[[File:F2-Race1\u306e\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30eb\uff11 (36974715682).jpg|thumb|left|Leclerc at the 2017 Formula 2 race at the [[Autodromo Nazionale Monza]] in Italy]]\nFor the Italian feature race, Leclerc was battling for the lead; on the final lap, however, he was involved in an accident with De Vries. After starting towards the back of the grid for the second consecutive sprint race, Leclerc managed to fight his way back to 9th position, albeit out of the points.\n\nWith a 57-point margin over Rowland heading into the penultimate rounds at Jerez, Leclerc gained his 8th pole position of the season, with both of his timed laps being good enough for pole position. In the feature race, Leclerc dominated most of the early stint on soft tyres and was able to overtake most of the runners on the alternate strategy. With 7 laps to go however, [[Nobuharu Matsushita]] collided with [[Santino Ferrucci]], which brought out the safety car. At the point that the race resumed, Leclerc was misinformed over team radio that it was the \"last lap\" even though there were four laps to go,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.motorsport.com/fia-f2/news/leclerc-column-jerez-title-mishap-lap-count-964048/|title=Leclerc column: How lap count mishap nearly delayed F2 title|work=Motorsport.com|access-date=6 February 2018|language=en}}</ref> so after pushing hard to build a gap Leclerc's tyres were \"overheated badly\"<ref name=\":1\" /> with several laps still to run, yet despite his tyres being \"completely gone\" by the end Leclerc managed to hold off a charging Rowland by 0.23 seconds,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fiaformula2.com/Results/?raceid=982&seasonid=174|title=Results \u2013 Formula 2|website=www.fiaformula2.com|access-date=6 February 2018}}</ref> and claim the FIA Formula 2 championship in his rookie season in the main F1 feeder series.\n\nIn claiming the championship, Leclerc became the youngest ever champion of the main support series for Formula 1 at 19 years 356 days old, and the first driver since [[Nico H\u00fclkenberg]] in 2009 to win the championship in their rookie season (a feat which only [[Nico Rosberg]] and [[Lewis Hamilton]] have previously accomplished) and is the only driver to claim a championship with the Dallara GP2/11 chassis in their rookie season.\n\nFor the sprint race, Leclerc started in 8th place, however due to his car's aggressive setup, he and his teammate, Antonio Fuoco, had to pit in the sprint race. Due to the aggressive pace of Leclerc however, he rose up through the field, yet because of the excessive wear on his tyres, he conceded 3 positions on the final lap and finished in 7th position.\n\nFor the final rounds at Abu Dhabi, Leclerc qualified in 6th place for the Feature race, his lowest starting position all season barring penalties. Despite this however, he managed to finish the highest of the alternate strategy runners in Abu Dhabi (Soft then Super Soft) in 4th place (he had made it up till 3rd until the final corner of the final lap where he was pipped by Antonio Fuoco). This position however was subsequently changed to second after the race winner, Oliver Rowland, and Fuoco were disqualified for excessive floor wear and under-inflated front tyres respectively.\n\nFor Leclerc's final race, he started in 7th position. He was initially able to make up 2 places but was running slower than the race leaders Alexander Albon and Nicholas Latifi. As the race progressed however, Leclerc started gaining time compared to his rivals and managed to take Latifi with a few laps to go. For the final three laps, DRS was disabled and yellow flags in the final sector meant that Leclerc was stuck behind Albon, however on the final lap, both drivers tangled, triggered by Leclerc nudging Albon, and both had a drag race which they constantly were pushing each other until Leclerc finally took the lead and won by 1.293 seconds, his final victory in his last ever F2 race.\n\n==Formula One career==\n===Test driver===\n====2016 season====\n\n[[File:Charles Leclerc 2017 Malaysia FP1.jpg|thumb|right|Leclerc testing for [[Sauber Motorsport|Sauber]] at the [[2017 Malaysian Grand Prix]]]]\nIn March 2016, it was announced that Leclerc would be one of two drivers to join the [[Ferrari Driver Academy]] and would act as development driver for [[Haas F1 Team]] and [[Scuderia Ferrari]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/leclerc-gets-ferrari-and-haas-development-role-676625/?s=1|title=Leclerc gets Ferrari and Haas development role|date=1 March 2016|accessdate=1 March 2016}}</ref> As part of his role as development driver, Leclerc participated in the first practice session of the [[2016 British Grand Prix]] and [[2016 German Grand Prix]] driving for [[Haas F1 Team|Haas]]. It was believed that if Leclerc won the [[GP3 Series]] championship, he would follow [[Daniil Kvyat]] and [[Valtteri Bottas]] direct from GP3 into F1 with Haas.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/f1/story/_/id/17129581/charles-leclerc-gp3-title-key-2017-f1-hopes|title=Charles Leclerc: GP3 title key to 2017 F1 hopes|date=23 July 2016|accessdate=6 September 2016}}</ref> However this was debunked by Haas team principal [[Guenther Steiner]] who said that Leclerc would progress to the [[2017 FIA Formula 2 Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://readmotorsport.com/2016/11/07/haas-steiner-gp3s-leclerc-to-drive-in-gp2/|title=Haas' Steiner: GP3's Leclerc to drive in GP2|date=7 November 2016|work=readmotorsport.com|accessdate=1 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2017 season====\nHe took part in the mid-season [[Hungaroring]] test following the [[2017 Hungarian Grand Prix|Hungarian Grand Prix]], driving the [[Ferrari SF70H]]. He was fastest on the first day of the test, running 98 laps in the process, but did not take part in the second day's test.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/headlines/2017/8/leclerc-heads-day-one-of-budapest-test.html|title=Leclerc heads day one of Budapest test for Ferrari|work=Formula1.com|access-date=8 August 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n===Sauber (2018)===\n[[File:2018 Chinese Grand Prix FP3 Charles Leclerc (39897914770) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Leclerc racing for Sauber at the [[2018 Chinese Grand Prix]]]]\nOn 2 December 2017, it was announced that Leclerc would make his racing debut in Formula One, signing with the [[Sauber F1 Team]] as regular driver for 2018,<ref name=\"Alfa Romeo Sauber\">{{cite news|last1=Noble|first1=Jonathan|title=Sauber confirms Ericsson alongside Leclerc for 2018|url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/sauber-confirms-ericsson-leclerc-for-2018-f1-season-985150/|accessdate=2 December 2017|work=[[Motorsport.com]]|publisher=[[Motorsport Network]]|date=2 December 2017}}</ref> thus marking the first appearance of a [[Mon\u00e9gasque Formula One driver]] since [[Olivier Beretta]] in {{F1|1994}}.{{refn|group=N|Beretta is the last Mon\u00e9gasque to compete in the sport, however the Dutch driver [[Robert Doornbos]] raced with a Mon\u00e9gasque licence in {{F1|2005}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fia.com/sport/Championships/F1/F1_Classifications/2005/Championship/2005.html|title=2005 FIA Formula One World Championship Classifications|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060314163635/http://www.fia.com/sport/Championships/F1/F1_Classifications/2005/Championship/2005.html|publisher=[[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de l'Automobile]]|accessdate=10 December 2017|archive-date=14 March 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref>}} At the {{F1 GP|2018|Azerbaijan}}, a sixth-place finish saw him become only the second Mon\u00e9gasque to score points in Formula One, after [[Louis Chiron]] finished on the podium at the [[1950 Monaco Grand Prix]].\n\nLeclerc ultimately almost entirely outqualified his team-mate [[Marcus Ericsson]] and ended up among the top 10 qualifiers on several occasions. He also finished in the points on several occasions, including multiple 7th-place finishes during the second half of the season, finishing 13th in the championship.\n\n===Ferrari (2019\u2013present)===\n====2019 season====\n[[File:Charles_Leclerc,_2019_Chinese_GP.jpg|thumb|right|Leclerc at the [[2019 Chinese Grand Prix]]]]\nOn 11 September 2018, [[Scuderia Ferrari]] announced the hiring of Leclerc for the {{f1|2019}} season, replacing [[Kimi R\u00e4ikk\u00f6nen]], who took his place at Sauber (now [[Alfa Romeo in Formula One|Alfa Romeo]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://formula1.ferrari.com/en/charles-leclerc-to-drive-for-scuderia-ferrari-in-2019/|title=Charles Leclerc to drive for Scuderia Ferrari in 2019|publisher=[[Scuderia Ferrari]]|date=11 September 2018|accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/ferrari-announces-leclerc-replacing-raikkonen/3174725/|title=Ferrari confirms Leclerc for 2019 F1 season|last=Mitchell|first=Scott|publisher=Motorsport.com|date=11 September 2018|accessdate=11 September 2018}}</ref> While initially only announced for 2019, a few days later, then-Ferrari team principal [[Maurizio Arrivabene]] indicated that Leclerc's contract was going to be four seasons long, running \"at least until 2022.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/leclerc-ferrari-contract-until-2022/3176733/|title=Ferrari signed Leclerc until at least 2022|last=Cooper|first=Adam|publisher=Motorsport.com|date=14 September 2018|accessdate=14 September 2018}}</ref> Leclerc made his first test day as an official Ferrari race driver on 28 November 2018 in [[Yas Marina Circuit|Abu Dhabi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.motorsport.com/f1/news/leclerc-fastest-ferrari-abu-dhabi-test/4305506/|title=Leclerc leads second morning of Abu Dhabi test|publisher=Motorsport.com|last=Mitchell|first=Scott|date=28 November 2018|accessdate=28 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn his first Grand Prix driving for Ferrari, he started and finished in fifth position at the [[2019 Australian Grand Prix|Australian Grand Prix]]. In his second qualifying for Ferrari, at the [[2019 Bahrain Grand Prix|Bahrain Grand Prix]], he qualified on pole position for the first time in his F1 career, having the fastest times in 2 of the 3 practice sessions and in all three qualifying sessions, setting a new track record, and becoming the youngest Ferrari pole-sitter.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/sport/formulauno/2019/03/31/news/formula_1_gp_barhain_hamilton_leclerc_bottas-222973148|title=Formula 1, Gp del Barhain: Hamilton vince ma ammette: \"Meritava la Ferrari di Leclerc\"|publisher=[[la Repubblica]]|date=31 March 2019|accessdate=31 March 2019|language=it}}</ref> Leclerc led for the majority of the race, but lost the lead and was overtaken by [[Lewis Hamilton]] and [[Valtteri Bottas]] due to his engine dropping a cylinder with a failed fuel injector. A late-race [[safety car]] prevented the charging [[Max Verstappen]] from taking 3rd place, leading to the first podium of Leclerc's F1 career.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://racer.com/2019/04/08/ferrari-identifies-cause-of-leclercs-bahrain-failure/|title=Ferrari identifies cause of Leclerc's Bahrain failure|author=Mark Glendenning|publisher=Racer|accessdate=9 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2019 Chinese Grand Prix|China]], Leclerc qualified 4th behind Vettel. After overtaking his teammate during the start, he was asked to yield and let Vettel pass, eventually finishing the race in 5th.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.skysports.com/f1/news/12433/11688577/ferrari-expand-on-charles-leclerc-sebastian-vettel-orders-in-china|title=Ferrari expand on Charles Leclerc, Sebastian Vettel orders in China|author=James Galloway|publisher=SkySports|accessdate=9 May 2019}}</ref> In [[2019 Azerbaijan Grand Prix|Azerbaijan]], he was the favourite for pole position until a crash in the second qualifying session ended his contention. He started 8th after penalties for the two Alfa Romeos and finished the race 5th with an extra point for the fastest lap of the race.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/f1/story/_/id/26627312/ferrari-explains-charles-leclerc-azerbaijan-grand-prix-strategy|title=Ferrari explains Charles Leclerc's Azerbaijan Grand Prix strategy|publisher=ESPN|author=Nate Saunders|accessdate=9 May 2019}}</ref> At the following race in [[2019 Monaco Grand Prix|Monaco]], he was eliminated in Q1 and started 15th due to Ferrari's erroneous strategy that kept him in the garage to save tyres, underestimating track evolution at the end of the qualifying session. He suffered a puncture and severe floor damage after a failed attempt to pass [[Nico H\u00fclkenberg]], leading to his second retirement at his home race. Leclerc qualified and finished 3rd in Canada, his second podium finish, behind the controversial 1-2 finish of Hamilton and teammate [[Sebastian Vettel]]. He would finish third again in [[2019 French Grand Prix|France]]. At the [[2019 Austrian Grand Prix|Austrian Grand Prix]], he qualified on pole position, the second pole of his Formula One career. He subsequently finished second after colliding with Red Bull's [[Max Verstappen]], having led for the major part of the race.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.austrian-grand-prix-2019-race-report-and-highlights.66QcACWZJJ2URf4fe46epG.html|title=Austrian Grand Prix 2019 race report and highlights - Verstappen completes stunning comeback win in Austria|website=www.formula1.com|accessdate=1 July 2019}}</ref> The incident was investigated by the stewards after the race, who deemed it a racing incident and decided against taking action.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-keeps-austrian-grand-prix-victory-after-stewards-investigation.63E1CoX0wclcdgYxfBsnPn.html|title=Verstappen keeps Austrian Grand Prix victory after stewards&#39; investigation|website=www.formula1.com|accessdate=2 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2019 British Grand Prix|British Grand Prix]], Leclerc qualified in 3rd ahead of Max Verstappen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.British-grand-prix-2019-qualifying-report-highlights.1QM7IStT79XC6iRfB2rM2l.html|title=Formula 1 - British Grand Prix 2019|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref> He eventually finished the race in 3rd place and was also voted 'Driver of the day' for defending his position against numerous attacks by Verstappen during the early stages of the race.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.hamilton-victorious-as-verstappen-and-vettel-collide-in-silverstone.3yHjP4nXKPkt4HYJQ7Bagt.html|title=2019 British Grand Prix|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref> This was his fourth consecutive podium finish of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.leclerc-declares-battling-silverstone-drive-the-most-fun-ive-had-in-f1.1YYTgHj5hME1kPfeOoDu4O.html|title=British Grand Prix|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=}}</ref> Despite having finished in the top two in all the three practice sessions, Leclerc qualified in 10th place at the [[2019 German Grand Prix|German Grand Prix]] after an issue with the fuel system prevented him from setting a lap time in the final qualifying session.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.German-grand-prix-2019-qualifying-report.7heCC9NEGU4pQZaGTm7Jpq.html|title=German Grand Prix 2019 qualifying report: Hamilton snatches German GP pole as Ferrari suffer catastrophic double breakdown &#124; Formula 1\u00ae|website=www.formula1.com}}</ref> In what turned out to be a sensational rain-hit race, he made his way up to 4th in the early laps. A questionable tactic by his team's strategists of installing soft tyres despite the track being too wet culminated in him losing control and crashing into the barriers on lap 29, leading to his second retirement of the season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.verstappen-storms-to-sensational-win-in-extraordinary-rain-hit-german-gp.4tqxtGz9gKxhlk9KCf0uZZ.html|title=German Grand Prix 2019 race report: Verstappen storms to sensational win in extraordinary rain-hit German Grand Prix|website=www.formula1.com|accessdate=29 July 2019}}</ref> At the [[2019 Hungarian Grand Prix|Hungarian Grand Prix]], Leclerc suffered a rear-end crash in qualifying but still completed the session. He ultimately finished the race in 4th place.\n\nAt the first race after the summer break, the [[2019 Belgian Grand Prix|Belgian Grand Prix]], Leclerc took his third pole position of the season alongside teammate [[Sebastian Vettel]] in 2nd\u2014the second Ferrari front row lockout of the season. During the race, Leclerc fended off the charging Mercedes of Lewis Hamilton to record his maiden Grand Prix win, making him the youngest ever Ferrari race winner. After the race he dedicated his maiden victory to his former competitor [[Anthoine Hubert]], who was killed in an accident during [[2019 Spa-Francorchamps FIA Formula 2 round|the previous day's Formula 2 feature race]] at the same circuit. At the [[2019 Italian Grand Prix|Italian Grand Prix]], Leclerc won the race from pole position after defending his position from both Mercedes drivers. He scored his third consecutive pole in [[2019 Singapore Grand Prix|Singapore]]. Initially leading the race, he finished in 2nd place after he was [[Glossary of motorsport terms#U|undercut]] by teammate Vettel. In [[2019 Russian Grand Prix|Russia]], he took his fourth consecutive pole position and his sixth of the season. Vettel passed Leclerc into the first corner and led for the first half of the race, before the team orchestrated an undercut in Leclerc's favour to let him retake the lead. Vettel retired from the race shortly after with a hybrid system failure, bringing out the [[virtual safety car]]. This greatly benefited the Mercedes drivers, who made their pit stops and eventually finished the race ahead of Leclerc in 3rd.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.formula1.com/en/latest/article.deliciously-ironic-that-vettel-failure-inspired-hamilton-victory-mercedes.5YoCZ0E8KAt6Hq58XWfn2M.html|title=\u2018Deliciously ironic\u2019 that Vettel failure inspired Hamilton victory \u2013 Mercedes|last=|first=|date=29 September 2019|website=www.formula1.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\nLeclerc qualified in 2nd in [[2019 Japanese Grand Prix|Japan]], but took damage in a first lap collision with Max Verstappen. He would go on to finish the race in 6th place, his worst finish of the season. Leclerc took his seventh pole position of the year in [[2019 Mexican Grand Prix|Mexico]] after Verstappen\u2014who had qualified in 1st place\u2014was handed a grid penalty for a [[Racing flags#Yellow flag|yellow flag]] infringement. He went on to finish the race in 4th place. After another 4th place finish in the [[2019 United States Grand Prix|United States]], a controversial collision with teammate Vettel caused Leclerc's third retirement of the season in [[2019 Brazilian Grand Prix|Brazil]], ending both drivers' races. Leclerc ended the season with a 3rd place finish in [[2019 Abu Dhabi Grand Prix|Abu Dhabi]].\n\nLeclerc ended the 2019 season in 4th place in the championship with 264 points, ahead of teammate Vettel. During his first season at Ferrari, he recorded ten podium finishes, two wins, four fastest laps and the most pole positions of any driver that season, with seven. Leclerc therefore became the first non-Mercedes driver to win the [[Pole position#Pole position trophy|Pole Position Award]]. He also became the first Mon\u00e9gasque to win a Formula One World Championship Grand Prix (although Louis Chiron had won a number of Grands Prix prior to the inaugural championship in {{F1|1950}}).\n\nLeclerc is due to drive for Ferrari until the end of 2024.<ref name=Leclerc2024/>\n\n==Racing record ==\n===Career summary===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%; text-align:center\"\n! Season\n! Series\n! Team\n! Races\n! Wins\n! Poles\n! FLaps\n! Podiums\n! Points\n! Position\n|-\n!rowspan=2| 2014\n|align=left| [[2014 Formula Renault 2.0 Alps Series|Formula Renault 2.0 Alps]]\n|align=left rowspan=2| [[Fortec Motorsports]]\n| 14\n| 2\n| 1\n| 0\n| 7\n| 199\n|style=\"background:#DFDFDF;\"| '''2nd'''\n|-\n|align=left| [[2014 Eurocup Formula Renault 2.0|Eurocup Formula Renault 2.0]]\n| 6\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 3\n| 0\n| NC\u2020\n|-\n!rowspan=2| 2015\n|align=left| [[2015 FIA Formula 3 European Championship|FIA Formula 3 European Championship]]\n|align=left rowspan=2| [[Van Amersfoort Racing]]\n| 33\n| 4\n| 3\n| 5\n| 13\n| 363.5\n| 4th\n|-\n|align=left| [[2015 Macau Grand Prix|Macau Grand Prix]]\n| 1\n| 0\n| 0\n| 0\n| 1\n| N/A\n|style=\"background:#DFDFDF;\"| '''2nd'''\n|-\n!rowspan=3| 2016\n|align=left rowspan=2| [[2016 Formula One World Championship|Formula One]]\n|align=left| [[Scuderia Ferrari]]\n|rowspan=2 colspan=7| Test driver\n|-\n|align=left| [[Haas F1 Team]]\n|-\n|align=left| [[2016 GP3 Series|GP3 Series]]\n|align=left| [[ART Grand Prix]]\n| 18\n| 3\n| 4\n| 4\n| 8\n| 202\n|style=\"background:#FFFFBF;\"| '''1st'''\n|-\n!rowspan=3| 2017\n|rowspan=2 align=left| [[2017 Formula One World Championship|Formula One]]\n|align=left| [[Scuderia Ferrari]]\n|rowspan=2 colspan=7| Test driver\n|-\n|align=le